Part 1 - Descriptive Statistics

Height Distribution

Lets look at how the height distribution in our dataset. Is the pattern is as we expected ? What would we expect ?

This is a continuous data - so one can use either a histogram or a smooth density plot for this.

ggplot(brfss_data, aes(x = Height))+ 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) + 
  labs(title = "Height Distribution",
       x = "Height (cm)",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 184 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

Now lets calculate the mean, and the SD values for this data and see how much of the peoples heights are within the 1 and 2 SD of the data.

# Compute mean and standard deviation
mean_height <- mean(brfss_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE) # Mean
sd_height <- sd(brfss_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE) # Standard Deviation

# Define ranges for 1 SD and 2 SD
one_sd_range <- c(mean_height - sd_height, mean_height + sd_height)
two_sd_range <- c(mean_height - 2 * sd_height, mean_height + 2 * sd_height)

# Calculate the percentage of people within each range
within_1sd <- sum(brfss_data$Height >= one_sd_range[1] & brfss_data$Height <= one_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(brfss_data) * 100
within_2sd <- sum(brfss_data$Height >= two_sd_range[1] & brfss_data$Height <= two_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(brfss_data) * 100

# Create a table
height_stats <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Mean Height", "1 SD Range", "2 SD Range", "% within 1 SD", "% within 2 SD"),
  Value = c(
    round(mean_height, 2),
    paste(round(one_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(one_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(two_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(two_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(within_1sd, 2), "%"),
    paste(round(within_2sd, 2), "%")
  )
)

height_stats

Now lets add these lines into our plot.

# Create the histogram with mean and SD lines
ggplot(brfss_data, aes(x = Height)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "slateblue", alpha = 0.7) + 
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean_height), linetype = "solid", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = one_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = one_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = two_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dotted", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = two_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dotted", size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Height Distribution with Mean and SD Lines",
       x = "Height (cm)",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Height Distribution - Sex

Could sex be a factor in height difference amongst people ? Lets look at their contribituon to our distribution plot.

# Create a combined histogram with color differentiation for Sex
ggplot(brfss_data, aes(x = Height, fill = Sex)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.7, position = "identity") + 
  labs(title = "Height Distribution by Sex",
       x = "Height (cm)",
       y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Female" = "lightpink", "Male" = "lightblue"))
## Warning: Removed 184 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

Okay it seems like females and males have diffferent mean and SD than one anoher. So lets calculate those stats for each sex seperately.

# Compute mean and standard deviation for each sex

# For Females
female_data <- subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female")
mean_female_height <- mean(female_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE)
sd_female_height <- sd(female_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE)

# For Males
male_data <- subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male")
mean_male_height <- mean(male_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE)
sd_male_height <- sd(male_data$Height, na.rm = TRUE)

# Define ranges for 1 SD and 2 SD for Females
female_one_sd_range <- c(mean_female_height - sd_female_height, mean_female_height + sd_female_height)
female_two_sd_range <- c(mean_female_height - 2 * sd_female_height, mean_female_height + 2 * sd_female_height)

# Define ranges for 1 SD and 2 SD for Males
male_one_sd_range <- c(mean_male_height - sd_male_height, mean_male_height + sd_male_height)
male_two_sd_range <- c(mean_male_height - 2 * sd_male_height, mean_male_height + 2 * sd_male_height)

# Calculate the percentage of people within each range (1 SD and 2 SD) for Females
female_within_1sd <- sum(female_data$Height >= female_one_sd_range[1] & female_data$Height <= female_one_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(female_data) * 100
female_within_2sd <- sum(female_data$Height >= female_two_sd_range[1] & female_data$Height <= female_two_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(female_data) * 100

# Calculate the percentage of people within each range (1 SD and 2 SD) for Males
male_within_1sd <- sum(male_data$Height >= male_one_sd_range[1] & male_data$Height <= male_one_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(male_data) * 100
male_within_2sd <- sum(male_data$Height >= male_two_sd_range[1] & male_data$Height <= male_two_sd_range[2], na.rm = TRUE) / nrow(male_data) * 100

# Create a table for Females, Males and not subsetted data
height_stats_sexes <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Mean Height", "1 SD Range", "2 SD Range", "% within 1 SD", "% within 2 SD"),
  Female = c(
    round(mean_female_height, 2),
    paste(round(female_one_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(female_one_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(female_two_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(female_two_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(female_within_1sd, 2), "%"),
    paste(round(female_within_2sd, 2), "%")
  ),
  Male = c(
    round(mean_male_height, 2),
    paste(round(male_one_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(male_one_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(male_two_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(male_two_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(male_within_1sd, 2), "%"),
    paste(round(male_within_2sd, 2), "%")
  ),
  All = c(
    round(mean_height, 2),
    paste(round(one_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(one_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(two_sd_range[1], 2), "-", round(two_sd_range[2], 2)),
    paste(round(within_1sd, 2), "%"),
    paste(round(within_2sd, 2), "%")
  )
)

height_stats_sexes

Now lets create the plots.

# Create histograms with SD lines for each sex using pre-computed stats

ggplot(brfss_data, aes(x = Height, fill = Sex)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.7, position = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~ Sex, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Female" = "lightpink", "Male" = "lightblue"))+
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  
  # Female SD Lines (only on Female plot)
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female"),
             aes(xintercept = mean_female_height), linetype = "solid", size = 0.5) +  # Mean line for females
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female"), 
             aes(xintercept = female_one_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5) +  # 1 SD min line for females
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female"), 
             aes(xintercept = female_one_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5) +  # 1 SD max line for females
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female"), 
             aes(xintercept = female_two_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5) +  # 2 SD min line for females
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Female"), 
             aes(xintercept = female_two_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5) +  # 2 SD max line for females
  
  # Male SD Lines (only on Male plot)
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male"), 
             aes(xintercept = mean_male_height), linetype = "solid", size = 0.5) +  # Mean line for males
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male"), 
             aes(xintercept = male_one_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5) +  # 1 SD min line for males
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male"), 
             aes(xintercept = male_one_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5) +  # 1 SD max line for males
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male"), 
             aes(xintercept = male_two_sd_range[1]), linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5) +  # 2 SD min line for males
  geom_vline(data = subset(brfss_data, Sex == "Male"), 
             aes(xintercept = male_two_sd_range[2]), linetype = "dotted", size = 0.5) +  # 2 SD max line for males
  
  labs(title = "Height Distribution by Sex with Mean and SD Lines",
       x = "Height (cm)",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Sampling

# Set seed for reproducibility and sample 10, 100, and 1000 rows
brfs_sub10 <- brfss_data %>% sample_n(10)
set.seed(2024)
brfs_sub100 <- brfss_data %>% sample_n(100)
set.seed(2024)
brfs_sub1000 <- brfss_data %>% sample_n(1000)
set.seed(2024)
brfs_sub10000 <- brfss_data %>% sample_n(10000)

# View the first few rows of each sample
head(brfs_sub10)
head(brfs_sub100)
head(brfs_sub1000)
head(brfs_sub10000)

Without setting seed, sampling would give us different results everytime.

#set.seed(2024)

Now lets see how confident we are with calculating mean from this data.
